- Enter or contact the host cells and directly cause cell death
- They may release toxins that kill cells at a distance, release enzymes that degrade tissue components or damage blood vessels and cause ischaemic necrosis.
- They can induce host cellular responses that although directed against the invader cause additional tissue damage usually by immune mediated mechanisms

\section*{Mechanisms of viral injury}

Viruses directly damage host cells by entering them and replicating at the host expense.Once the viruses' one in the hosts cell, they cause tissue damage in a number of ways.
i. Inhibit host cell DNA,RNA or protein synthesis e.g. polio virus
ii. Viral protein may insert into the host cells plasma membrane and directly damage its integrity or promote cell fusion (e.g. HIV, measles viruses and herpes virus.
iii. Viruses may manipulate programmed cell death.(HIV)
iv. Viruses may lyse host cells, e.g. influenza virus replication, yellow fever, neurons by polio, rabies virus.
v. Host cells may induce immune system leading to attack the virus- infected cells
vi. Viruses may damage cells involved in host antimicrobial defense leading to secondary infections e.g. damages to epithelial cells
vii. Viral killing of one cell type may cause death of other cells e.g. polio
viii. Some viruses can cause cell proliferation and transformation leading to development of carcinoma e.g. Ebstein burr virus and hepatitis B virus

